\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 4.            Cortusa}             L.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By L.F. Ferguson.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial herbs. Leaves basal, long-petiolate. Inflorescence scapose, umbellate, bracteate. Corolla much longer than calyx, divided to 1/3; limb infundibuliform, divided to 1/2 or more. Filaments with dilated base, connate to form a ring. Capsule ovoid to subcylindrical; valves 5. Seeds numerous.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. C. matthioli} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 144 (1753). Plant 20-40 cm, pubescent and with ferruginous hairs throughout. Leaves 10-25 cm; petiole up to 17 cm. Lamina reniform to suborbicular, cordate at base, up to 12 cm wide, lobed to ¼ of radius; lobes coarsely and irregularly dentate. Scape 15-35 cm. Bracts 5-15 mm, laciniate. Flowers 5-20. Calyx divided to ½-way, lobes acute to acuminate. Corolla c. 1 cm, 1½-2 times as long as calyx divided to 1/3, purple-violet. Stamens included, apiculate. Style exserted. Capsule (4-)5-7(-9) mm. Seeds c. 40, polyhedral, with narrow wings on the angles. 2n = 24.{\i  Mountain woods and other damp places; calcicole. C. & E. Russia; mountains of S.E. & S.C. Europe from Bulgaria and E. Carpathians to S.W. Alps.} Au Bu Cz Ga Ge He It Ju Po Rm Rs (N, C, W, E).
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  Small plants from Ural, subglabrous and lacking ferruginous hairs, with dentate bracts, deeply lobed leaves and few-flowered umbels have been called{\b  C. altaica} Losinsk., {\i Acta Inst. Bot. Acad. Sci. URSS} ({\i Ser.} 1) {\b 3}: 243 (1936), but they merge into and are not clearly separated from {\b 1}.
